<div class="flexy" hidden="@C5">
    <h2> Budgeting for November </h2>
        <p>November finds itself in the middle of the last quarter of the year. October was all about the experience of the Fall season, for which we prepared in September (when it comes to our appearance and our attitude). The combination of finding comfort in the season of fall and meticulous spending, with some extra attention on savings, was, in October, our focus. </p>
        <p><a href="https://adminique.be/budgeting-for-october/">How is or was your October?</a> Have you found cozy comfort? Was your spending meticulous? I hope that you have started off the quarter beautifully. </p>
        <h3>Properties of November</h3>
        <p>November finds itself in the midst of a month that we devoted to philosophy and meticulous spending, and a month that is about togetherness and holidays: the last month of the year. In November, in the climax of the fall season, may our philosophy be even deeper than that of October, and may our spending be even more meticulous. </p>
        <p>In September, we intensively revised our paths. In October, we have practiced philosophy. Now, it is time to apply our, in October, deepened philosophy to the renewed pathways we embarked on in September. We have gained new experiences on our new paths. What have we learned from this? The things that we have learned now, could define the new objectives that we will state for January. </p>
        <p>You see, November is about change. Just like trees are in transition for the winter season with their leaves turning color, in October, we used more philosophy than before, because in the winter we limit our range of activities, which results in more time with philosophy and us. The turning color of leaves is a rather internal process, in comparison to the external where the leaves actually fall from the branches. In that same way, at first there is only philosophy, but later on the seasons might demand more physical labor for our households as well. In November, we change our physical and mental ways in preparation of December. </p>
        <p>What is most remarkable about November is that, given that December is the most traditionally festive month of the year, November finds itself at the dawn of the end-of-year festivity. It might feel as “the silence before the storm”. In “the silence”, we reflect on our earlier lessons and we find ourselves in the preparatory atmosphere of November as we are thinking ahead in preparation of further seasonal change. </p>
        <h3>Principles of November</h3>
        <p>There are no budgeting principles for November, because our spending is just as meticulous as in October. In November, we focus on our lessons of October, and clean up our administrations so that we can maximally enjoy ourselves in December. You might notice that – in comparison to August and September – no special expenses are made in both October and November. The more we manage to save in these months, the more lavishly we can live in December.</p>
        <p>Philosophy is inexpensive. You might have broadened your perspective over the month. I mean, you have developed your own philosophy on life for as long as you have lived. But just like nature and life are ever-evolving, the content of our minds is ever-evolving (along with that same process). You might still feel the psychological effects of a good book that you have read. What aspects of yourself does your new philosophy touch upon? Definitively change your philosophy on those aspects with philosophy in November. In December, you will appreciate that you have done this. </p>
        <p>In terms of taxation, for December, the government comes knocking at our doors to ask how our last quarter, as well as our entire year has been. Do not let this be a surprise. That is why, for November’s closings, we include the preparatory work of administration for December, the last quarter and the end of the year. </p>
</div>
<div class="flexy" hidden="@C4">
    <h2> Budgeting for December </h2>
        <p>Let us cheer, because December is here! It is the last month of the year, within which we have plenty to reflect upon. I hope that you are starting December off with a clear perspective, with the lessons that you have defined over October and November. May the togetherness of December lead you to new insights that help you define your direction in and after January. </p>
        <h3>Properties of December</h3>
        <p>In December, one must be free of any worry: may you enjoy yourself. May the practice of philosophy have been helpful in the process of reflecting on your path, so that it is clear to you where you stand right in this moment. And may your administration be organized enough for you to make expenses without having to overthink them.</p>
        <p>The first property of December is psychological. In terms of tolerance, people push themselves beyond their limits, because togetherness is a central factor. In contrast with the togetherness of December, we have been alone in our processes of personal growth. And even though our paths are all unique, we all acknowledge that everyone has worked hard over the year and that therefore, in December, we are extra kind to each other. Sure, they say “naughty or nice”, so there could be reason for some serious honesty, but all in all, we grow together in December.</p>
        <p>The second property of December is economic. December is a very definitive month in terms of the decisions that you have made over the year and where you stand now. That “behavioral economic” aspect goes in combination with what you will do for your community that month. </p>
        <p>The last property of December is also psychological. After all, it is the last month of the year. May you feel proud of yourself when you reflect on how your year was. It is important that you reflect on your year. Make sure that you note the lessons that you have learnt, and use them to define your objectives for January: the definition of your New Year’s Resolution. </p>
        <h3>Financial Principles of December</h3>
        <p>We have been spending money meticulously and making sure that our administrations are neat over October and November. This, amongst other reasons, to enjoy December’s togetherness to the fullest. May the most cherishable moments of togetherness be the yield of our hard work, and may you be able to reward those who have been working hard alongside you with something that you love to give. It leads to the following financial principles:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>To be mindful with our December budgets</li>
            <li>To keep our administrations neat</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>To be Mindful with our December Budgets</h4>
        <p>It would be a waste of our savings to mindlessly spend money on things that must be of symbolic value, without having been mindful about that which must have symbolic value first. Make sure that you take some time to reflect on the symbolic message(s) that you would like to convey. (Perhaps write it down first.) And then, after careful reflection, enjoy yourself when you are undertaking the steps that need to be taken to practice the art of giving. </p>
        <h4>To Keep our Administrations Neat</h4>
        <p>It is the closing month of the last quarter of the year. After administrative reflection in October and administrative cleanup in November, enjoy the fruit of your labor by, in December, keeping your administration up-to-date constantly. This makes it easier to find elements of administration when we need to, for evaluation purposes, for example. </p>
    </div>
