<div class="flexy" hidden="@C2">
    <h2>About The Responsible Expense Calculator</h2>
        <p>You might be wondering: <i>“What is the purpose of a “Responsible Expense Calculator?”</i> or <i>“When would I use the “Responsible Expense Calculator?”</i> Well, the Responsible Expense Calculator is here to simplify making financial decisions in the context of “expensiveness”. It can be used to judge an expense as a call upon your budget. </p>
        <p>Here are some statements that exemplify scenarios in which the Responsible Expense Calculator could be used:</p>
        <p class="accent">“I only have limited funds to expend, but I would like to undertake something fun with my friends.”</p>
        <p class="accent">“I would like to buy this dress, but I have bills to pay.”</p>
        <p>The next question that might arise could be: <i>“Why is there a savings-ratio?”</i> </p>
        <p>Because maybe, when it comes to making expenses, the first thing that comes to mind is not how much you would not like to spend. There is a source of funds and there price to pay, in simple terms. But that you are buying something does not mean that the source of funds must be left empty. The savings-ratio is here to define how much of your budget must remain untouched.</p>
        <p>Here is an example:</p>
        <p>Individual A has a budget of €2000. Of that €2000, the individual would like to save €500 for reserved expenses. And he or she would like to buy a new phone that costs €1000. </p>
        <p>So the €500 of reserved expenses means that there is a savings-ratio of (“about”) 25%. Individual A, thus, has €1500 to spend. The €1000 for a new phone is affordable to individual A, but that €1000 takes up more than half of the budget its remainder could be considered as “risky”.  </p>
